│ An ifunc resolver is a function that returns a pointer to the function that should be      │
│ called. The `globalopt` pass tries to optimize ifuncs by resolving them at compile time if │
│ possible. One of the optimizations, `OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs`, attempts to do this by     │
│ analyzing the resolver function to determine the possible functions it can return, based   │
│ on target features.                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Understanding the Issue                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ The provided reproducer defines an ifunc `@i1` with a resolver function `@f1`. The         │
│ resolver function `@f1` is defined as:                                                     │
│ ```llvm                                                                                    │
│ define ptr @f1() {                                                                         │
│   unreachable                                                                              │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ This function has no `return` statement; its only basic block terminates with an           │
│ `unreachable` instruction.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` function in `GlobalOpt.cpp` iterates through the basic      │
│ blocks of the resolver function, looking for `return` instructions to identify the         │
│ functions that can be returned. It uses a helper function, `collectVersions`, to extract   │
│ these functions from the return value.                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that if the resolver function contains no `return` instructions,            │
│ `collectVersions` is never called, and the list of potential callees (`Callees`) remains   │
│ empty. The code then hits an assertion: `!Callees.empty()`, which assumes that at least    │
│ one callee version will always be found if the resolver is processed. This assumption is   │
