│ \"Expecting successful collection of versions\"` clearly indicates that the program state  │
│ at that point violates the assumption that at least one function version would be          │
│ collected from the resolver.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause is an         │
│ incomplete assumption in the `OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` implementation. The code that      │
│ collects the versions is:\n\n```cpp\n//                                                    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2545-2552\nSmallVector<Function *> Callees;\nif      │
│ (any_of(*Resolver, [&TTI, &Callees](BasicBlock &BB) {\n      if (auto *Ret =               │
│ dyn_cast_or_null<ReturnInst>(BB.getTerminator()))\n        if (!collectVersions(TTI,       │
│ Ret->getReturnValue(), Callees))\n          return true;\n      return false;\n    }))\n   │
│ continue;\n```\n\nThis loop iterates through the basic blocks of the resolver. For the     │
│ given reproducer, the resolver `@f1` has a single basic block ending in `unreachable`. The │
│ `dyn_cast_or_null<ReturnInst>` check fails for this block's terminator. Consequently,      │
│ `collectVersions` is never called, and the `Callees` vector remains empty.\n\nImmediately  │
│ following this loop is the assertion:\n\n```cpp\n//                                        │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2554\nassert(!Callees.empty() && \"Expecting         │
│ successful collection of versions\");\n```\n\nThis assertion incorrectly assumes that any  │
│ resolver processed will yield at least one version. It does not account for valid          │
│ resolvers that might not have any `return` instructions (e.g., those that unconditionally  │
│ lead to `unreachable` or are part of a non-returning function). The logic should be able   │
│ to handle this case gracefully by simply skipping the optimization for such an             │
│ `ifunc`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add a check after the version   │
│ collection loop to see if the `Callees` vector is empty. If it is, it means no versions    │
│ could be determined, and we should proceed to the next `ifunc` in the module without       │
│ attempting further optimization on the current one.\n\n**File**:                           │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp`\n\n**Edit Point**: Insert a check before the       │
│ assertion at line 2554.\n\n```cpp\n// llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2552\n         │
│ continue;\n \n+    if (Callees.empty())\n+      continue;\n+\n     assert(!Callees.empty() │
│ && \"Expecting successful collection of versions\");\n```\n\nThis change ensures that if   │
│ no versions are found, the pass doesn't crash and simply moves on, which is the correct    │
│ behavior.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe crash in `globalopt` is due to a faulty assertion    │
│ that doesn't consider `ifunc` resolvers that never return a function pointer. By adding a  │
│ simple check for an empty list of collected callees and continuing to the next `ifunc` if  │
│ none are found, we make the optimization pass more robust and prevent the crash. This      │
│ allows LLVM to correctly process modules containing such `ifunc` definitions."})           │
