  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `globalopt` pass is designed to
perform various interprocedural optimizations on LLVM modules. One of its tasks is to resolve
indirect function calls made through `ifunc` (indirect function) globals. An `ifunc` has an
associated \"resolver\" function, which is executed at load time to determine the actual
function to be called. The `OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` function within `globalopt` attempts to
statically determine the outcome of this resolution at compile time based on target
features.\n\nThe issue arises with the provided reproducer:\n\n```llvm\ndefine ptr @f1() {\n
unreachable\n}\n\n@i1 = ifunc void(), ptr @f1\n```\n\nHere, the resolver function `@f1` does
not return any value; its entry block terminates with an `unreachable` instruction. The
`OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` logic iterates through the resolver's basic blocks, looking for
`return` instructions to identify the set of possible functions (versions) that the `ifunc`
can resolve to. When it encounters a resolver like `@f1` with no `return` instructions, it
fails to collect any versions. This leads to an empty `Callees` vector, which subsequently
triggers an assertion `!Callees.empty()`, causing the compiler to crash.\n\n### 2. Analyzing
`opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace confirms that the crash occurs within the
`OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs` function at `llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2554`. The
assertion message `!Callees.empty() && \"Expecting successful collection of versions\"`
clearly indicates that the program state at that point violates the assumption that at least
one function version would be collected from the resolver.\n\n### 3. Root Cause
Analysis\n\nThe root cause is an incomplete assumption in the `OptimizeNonTrivialIFuncs`
implementation. The code that collects the versions is:\n\n```cpp\n//
llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2545-2552\nSmallVector<Function *> Callees;\nif
(any_of(*Resolver, [&TTI, &Callees](BasicBlock &BB) {\n      if (auto *Ret =
dyn_cast_or_null<ReturnInst>(BB.getTerminator()))\n        if (!collectVersions(TTI,
Ret->getReturnValue(), Callees))\n          return true;\n      return false;\n    }))\n
continue;\n```\n\nThis loop iterates through the basic blocks of the resolver. For the given
reproducer, the resolver `@f1` has a single basic block ending in `unreachable`. The
`dyn_cast_or_null<ReturnInst>` check fails for this block's terminator. Consequently,
`collectVersions` is never called, and the `Callees` vector remains empty.\n\nImmediately
following this loop is the assertion:\n\n```cpp\n//
llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2554\nassert(!Callees.empty() && \"Expecting successful
collection of versions\");\n```\n\nThis assertion incorrectly assumes that any resolver
processed will yield at least one version. It does not account for valid resolvers that might
not have any `return` instructions (e.g., those that unconditionally lead to `unreachable` or
are part of a non-returning function). The logic should be able to handle this case gracefully
by simply skipping the optimization for such an `ifunc`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to add a check after the version collection loop to see if the
`Callees` vector is empty. If it is, it means no versions could be determined, and we should
proceed to the next `ifunc` in the module without attempting further optimization on the
current one.\n\n**File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp`\n\n**Edit Point**: Insert a
check before the assertion at line 2554.\n\n```cpp\n//
llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/GlobalOpt.cpp:2552\n       continue;\n \n+    if (Callees.empty())\n+
continue;\n+\n     assert(!Callees.empty() && \"Expecting successful collection of
versions\");\n```\n\nThis change ensures that if no versions are found, the pass doesn't crash
and simply moves on, which is the correct behavior.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe crash in
`globalopt` is due to a faulty assertion that doesn't consider `ifunc` resolvers that never
return a function pointer. By adding a simple check for an empty list of collected callees and
continuing to the next `ifunc` if none are found, we make the optimization pass more robust
and prevent the crash. This allows LLVM to correctly process modules containing such `ifunc`
definitions.",
